The paper focuses on explaining the behavior of deep neural networks, specifically convolutional neural networks, which are commonly used in computer vision tasks. Therefore, cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of an influence measure to identify influential neurons, which falls under the category of interpretability and explainability in AI, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) a likely sub-category as well. The paper also evaluates the approach using various datasets, which falls under the category of machine learning, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of individual features to make decisions and distinguish related instances, which falls under the category of natural language processing, making cs.CL (Computation and Language) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of deep neural networks, which falls under the category of neural and evolutionary computing, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category.
